{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630381"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:17:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17317"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17317"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.05,0.14,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69861"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10007"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17317"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55317"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10045"},{"type":"tags","id":"10476"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23447"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23451"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69861"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of water absorption in the colon?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Passive movement following sodium absorption","Primary active transport using ATP","Active transport through aquaporin channels","Facilitated diffusion via carrier proteins","Direct coupling to glucose transport"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWater absorption in the colon occurs through \u003Cstrong\u003Epassive movement following sodium absorption\u003C/strong\u003E. Sodium is actively absorbed through epithelial sodium channels, creating an osmotic gradient that drives water absorption through the paracellular pathway and cell membranes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport through aquaporin channels\u003C/strong\u003E - aquaporins are membrane proteins that facilitate passive transport of water molecules across cell membranes via osmosis, they do not use active transport\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion via carrier proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Water moves by simple diffusion, not through carrier proteins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect coupling to glucose transport\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in the small intestine but not the colon\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary active transport using ATP\u003C/strong\u003E - Water movement is passive and does not directly require ATP\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe absorption of approximately 1.5 L of water per day in the colon is essential for maintaining fluid balance. This process is enhanced by short-chain fatty acids produced by colonic bacteria, which stimulate both sodium and water absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The colon absorbs approximately 1.5 L of water per day through osmotic gradients created by sodium absorption.","Sodium absorption in the colon occurs primarily through epithelial sodium channels in the luminal membrane."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Boron W. F., Boulpaep E. L. Medical Physiology. (3rd edition). US. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55317"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17317"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55317"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-12T21:07:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-12T21:08:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10007"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69861"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"20